<refentry xmlns="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" xmlns:svg="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:db="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" version="5.0-subset Scilab" xml:id="steadycos">
  <refnamediv>
    <refname>steadycos</refname>
    <refpurpose>Finds an equilibrium state of a general dynamical system described by a scicos diagram</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>
  <refsynopsisdiv>
    <title>Calling Sequence</title>
    <synopsis>[X,U,Y,XP]=steadycos(scs_m,X,U,Y,Indx,Indu,Indy [,Indxp [,param ] ])</synopsis>
  </refsynopsisdiv>
  <refsection id="Module_steadycos">
    <title>Module</title>
    <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>
        <para>
          <link linkend="scicos_manual">Scicos</link>
        </para>
      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>
  </refsection>
  <refsection id="Description_steadycos">
    <title>Description</title>
    <para>
This function finds the steady state for a given system described by a Scicos diagram. The diagram consists in general of a Super block with input and output port blocks. The steady state concern only the continuous-time dynamics.  
</para>
    <para>
</para>
    <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[ 
[X,U,Y,XP]=steadycos(scs_m,X,U,Y,Indx,Indu,Indy [,Indxp [,param ] ])
 ]]></programlisting>
  </refsection>
  <refsection id="Parameters_steadycos">
    <title>Parameters</title>
    <itemizedlist>
      <listitem>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">scs_m :</emphasis> a Scicos data structure</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">X :</emphasis> column vector. Continuous state. Can be set to [] if zero.</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">U :</emphasis> column vector. Input. Can be set to [] if zero.</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">Y :</emphasis> column vector. Output. Can be set to [] if zero.</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">Indx :</emphasis> index of entries of X that are not fixed. If all can vary, set to 1:$</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">Indu :</emphasis> index of entries of U that are not fixed. If all can vary, set to 1:$</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">Indy :</emphasis> index of entries of Y that are not fixed. If all can vary, set to 1:$</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">Indxp :</emphasis> index of entries of XP (derivative of x) that need not be zero. If all can vary, set to 1:$. Default [].</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">param :</emphasis> list with two elements (default list(1.d-6,0)). param(1): scalar. Perturbation level for linearization; the following variation is used del([x;u])_i = param(1)+param(1)*1d-4*abs([x;u])_i. param(2): scalar. Time t.</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">X :</emphasis> steady state X</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">U :</emphasis> stationary input U</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">Y :</emphasis> output corresponding to steady state found</para>
      </listitem>
      <listitem>
        <para><emphasis role="bold">XP :</emphasis> derivative of the state corresponding to steady state found</para>
      </listitem>
    </itemizedlist>
  </refsection>
